<i>And I got embedded with the US Military</i>

425
00:27:05,124 --> 00:27:09,174
<i>as our troops trained</i>
<i>for America's most recent wars.</i>

426
00:27:09,670 --> 00:27:10,960
[gentle piano music playing]

427
00:27:11,046 --> 00:27:13,376
<i>It became a year-long project.</i>

428
00:27:14,883 --> 00:27:20,263
<i>We went to Arlington Cemetery</i>
<i>as one of the important sessions.</i>

429
00:27:21,390 --> 00:27:28,020
And I noticed this lady takes a fold-out
picnic chair every day to her son's grave,

430
00:27:29,314 --> 00:27:31,654
<i>and reads to her son's gravestone.</i>

431
00:27:31,733 --> 00:27:33,363
[piano music continues]

432
00:27:33,443 --> 00:27:35,403
<i>I was just devastated.</i>

433
00:27:36,864 --> 00:27:38,704
<i>And if it meant something to me,</i>

434
00:27:38,782 --> 00:27:41,662
<i>there's just a chance</i>
<i>it means something to other people.</i>

435
00:27:42,494 --> 00:27:44,834
Is it wrong to be
a Muslim in this country?

436
00:27:44,913 --> 00:27:46,503
The answer is, "No, that's not America."

437
00:27:46,582 --> 00:27:49,002
[Powell] <i>I feel strongly</i>
<i>about this particular point</i>

438
00:27:49,084 --> 00:27:51,554
<i>because of a picture I saw in a magazine.</i>

439
00:27:51,628 --> 00:27:55,798
<i>It was a photo-essay about troops</i>
<i>who were serving in Iraq and Afghanistan.</i>

440
00:27:56,216 --> 00:27:59,546
<i>And one picture was of a mother</i>
<i>in Arlington Cemetery.</i>

441
00:27:59,636 --> 00:28:02,716
<i>She had her head</i>
<i>on the headstone of her son's grave,</i>

442
00:28:02,806 --> 00:28:06,766
<i>and you could see his awards,</i>
<i>Purple Heart, Bronze Star.</i>

443
00:28:06,852 --> 00:28:09,482
<i>He was 20 years old. He died in Iraq.</i>

444
00:28:09,563 --> 00:28:11,153
<i>And then at the very top,</i>

445
00:28:11,231 --> 00:28:13,821
<i>it had a crescent and a star</i>
<i>of the Islamic faith.</i>

446
00:28:14,359 --> 00:28:16,529
<i>He was an American and he gave his life.</i>

447
00:28:18,238 --> 00:28:20,028
<i>There was something I had wanted to say</i>

448
00:28:20,115 --> 00:28:24,865
about the intolerance that is
being shown increasingly in 2008,

449
00:28:24,953 --> 00:28:26,253
and frankly it has continued.

450
00:28:27,581 --> 00:28:30,331
And so I said, "How can I really
illustrate and demonstrate this?"

451
00:28:30,417 --> 00:28:31,997
And bam, there was the photo.

452
00:28:34,880 --> 00:28:36,590
[Platon] <i>That was the beginning.</i>

453
00:28:36,673 --> 00:28:39,223
<i>I realized that from now on,</i>

454
00:28:39,801 --> 00:28:42,551
the hero is the person that inspires us

455
00:28:42,638 --> 00:28:46,228
to think again about our own moral compass

456
00:28:46,975 --> 00:28:50,595
and our own responsibility
as global citizens.

457
00:28:52,356 --> 00:28:55,976
Platon talks truth to power in his work,

458
00:28:56,068 --> 00:28:57,568
and he talks truth to power

459
00:28:57,653 --> 00:29:00,743
in the subjects
that he chooses to shoot sometimes.

460
00:29:02,699 --> 00:29:04,369
[Platon] <i>Human Rights Watch approached me</i>

461
00:29:04,451 --> 00:29:06,751
<i>and they said, "There's this country</i>
<i>called Burma</i>

462
00:29:06,828 --> 00:29:09,118
<i>that's run by a brutal military regime.</i>

463
00:29:09,206 --> 00:29:12,626
<i>No one's talking about it.</i>
<i>Can we do something about it?"</i>

464
00:29:13,669 --> 00:29:15,549
<i>We published all the work,</i>

465
00:29:16,171 --> 00:29:17,211
<i>and it blew up!</i>

466
00:29:18,257 --> 00:29:22,217
That sort of aspect of pictures
can change the world.

467
00:29:23,095 --> 00:29:26,845
<i>These stories will be placed</i>
<i>in publications</i>

468
00:29:26,932 --> 00:29:32,942
<i>and that collectively brings a focus</i>
<i>on horrible situations</i>

469
00:29:33,021 --> 00:29:34,821
<i>that exist in the world.</i>

470
00:29:35,899 --> 00:29:40,029
[Platon] <i>I realized if I were to</i>
<i>raise my own money,</i>

471
00:29:40,112 --> 00:29:42,492
<i>I could go to my friends</i>
<i>in the NGO community,</i>

472
00:29:42,572 --> 00:29:46,912
<i>and I'll say, "Give me your stories</i>
<i>and I will bring them to life."</i>

473
00:29:47,619 --> 00:29:51,919
[Pollack] <i>Platon came to me</i>
<i>with an incredible series of pictures</i>

474
00:29:51,999 --> 00:29:55,709
on undocumented migrants in this country.

475
00:29:56,837 --> 00:29:59,717
<i>He was interested</i>
<i>in families that were being torn apart,</i>

476
00:30:00,757 --> 00:30:05,097
<i>and we were able to publish that work.</i>
<i>And not only did he photograph them,</i>

477
00:30:05,178 --> 00:30:06,428
<i>but he interviewed them.</i>

478
00:30:07,597 --> 00:30:09,637
<i>It was an incredible series.</i>

479
00:30:12,019 --> 00:30:14,519
[Platon]<i> And my job</i>
<i>is to be the bridge builder.</i>

480
00:30:15,772 --> 00:30:20,742
<i>And we're nothing as human beings</i>
<i>if we don't experience that connection.</i>

481
00:30:22,863 --> 00:30:26,203
<i>So I founded The People's Portfolio</i>

482
00:30:26,283 --> 00:30:28,793
<i>to help tell these important stories</i>
<i>of our time.</i>

483
00:30:30,037 --> 00:30:31,747
[African drumming]

484
00:30:41,173 --> 00:30:42,723
<i>What brought me to Congo</i>

485
00:30:42,799 --> 00:30:48,259
<i>was a chance meeting with this</i>
<i>incredible man called Dr. Mukwege.</i>

486
00:30:49,014 --> 00:30:50,724
<i>He's a gynecologist.</i>

487
00:30:50,807 --> 00:30:52,517
<i>He set up a small practice</i>

488
00:30:52,601 --> 00:30:56,651
<i>to help women give birth</i>
<i>in a happy, normal environment.</i>

489
00:30:56,730 --> 00:30:58,770
<i>But what started to happen,</i>

490
00:30:59,691 --> 00:31:02,361
<i>women were arriving</i>
<i>at the gates of his hospital</i>

491
00:31:02,444 --> 00:31:07,824
<i>who experienced the most traumatic</i>
<i>sexual violence you could imagine.</i>

492
00:31:10,285 --> 00:31:13,825
<i>He's dealing with</i>
<i>this trauma of civilization.</i>

493
00:31:15,332 --> 00:31:17,752
<i>He invited me to his hospital</i>
<i>with my team.</i>

494
00:31:18,460 --> 00:31:20,630
<i>I was committed to see</i>
<i>if I could help him.</i>

495
00:31:22,381 --> 00:31:25,511
<i>And I said I would love</i>
<i>to photograph the survivors</i>

496
00:31:25,592 --> 00:31:28,052
<i>and I would like to tell</i>
<i>a broader story as well.</i>

497
00:31:30,347 --> 00:31:33,017
<i>So I hooked up with two partners,</i>

498
00:31:33,100 --> 00:31:34,980
<i>the Panzi Hospital Foundation</i>

499
00:31:35,852 --> 00:31:39,152
<i>and then another organization</i>
<i>called Physicians for Human Rights</i>.

500
00:31:39,731 --> 00:31:42,401
<i>And we all formed</i>
<i>this giant network together.</i>

501
00:31:42,484 --> 00:31:43,614
[Mukwege] Hello, Platon.

502
00:31:48,532 --> 00:31:50,032
It's been a long journey.

503
00:31:50,117 --> 00:31:54,657
-And we're here for you, my whole team.
-Thank you.

504
00:31:56,206 --> 00:31:58,746
[Platon] <i>This was the hardest mission</i>
<i>I've ever put together.</i>

505
00:31:58,834 --> 00:32:01,504
<i>It was a three-year project to plan.</i>

506
00:32:01,586 --> 00:32:03,706
-[people singing]
-[drums banging]

507
00:32:18,603 --> 00:32:21,063
[Platon] <i>People need to know</i>
<i>what's going on in Congo.</i>

508
00:32:21,773 --> 00:32:25,613
<i>And my job is to build that bridge</i>
<i>in a solid way.</i>

509
00:32:25,694 --> 00:32:31,034
<i>The power of the content,</i>
<i>that's the whole point of design.</i>

510
00:32:31,116 --> 00:32:34,576
<i>That moment when</i>
<i>you feel something very powerful.</i>

511
00:32:35,203 --> 00:32:36,413
[all singers] Amen.

512
00:32:37,038 --> 00:32:39,788
[Mukwege<i> </i>in Swahili]
He is a famous photographer

513
00:32:39,875 --> 00:32:41,835
and is known all over the world.

514
00:32:42,544 --> 00:32:43,424
Platon.

515
00:32:43,503 --> 00:32:45,513
[crowd clapping and laughing]

516
00:32:48,884 --> 00:32:50,554
[Mukwege] Glory be to the Lord.

517
00:32:50,635 --> 00:32:51,755
[all] Amen.

518
00:32:54,431 --> 00:32:57,731
[Platon] <i>The crisis in the Congo</i>
<i>is very complicated.</i>

519
00:32:59,227 --> 00:33:01,307
<i>It's a mineral-rich country,</i>

520
00:33:01,396 --> 00:33:02,896
<i>but with that mineral wealth</i>

521
00:33:02,981 --> 00:33:08,781
<i>has also come great corruption,</i>
<i>rebels, civilians, militia.</i>

522
00:33:08,862 --> 00:33:10,452
[gunfire]

523
00:33:11,072 --> 00:33:13,582
<i>The underlying notion of the Congo</i>

524
00:33:13,658 --> 00:33:16,998
<i>is that if you want territory,</i>
<i>you take it.</i>

525
00:33:18,622 --> 00:33:21,082
<i>And the easiest and cheapest way</i>
<i>to take the land</i>

526
00:33:21,166 --> 00:33:25,046
<i>begins with using rape</i>
<i>as a weapon of warfare.</i>

527
00:33:29,341 --> 00:33:32,051
<i>Rape is cheaper than bullets.</i>

528
00:33:37,349 --> 00:33:40,099
We all just have to be aware.

529
00:33:40,185 --> 00:33:41,975
We're dealing with women

530
00:33:42,062 --> 00:33:44,942
who have been through
the worst circumstances in their lives,

531
00:33:45,023 --> 00:33:46,693
and we're a bunch of guys.

532
00:33:47,317 --> 00:33:49,027
<i>Just be gentle. All right?</i>

533
00:33:49,653 --> 00:33:53,573
<i>I'm going to photograph</i>
<i>one at a time, maybe two together.</i>

534
00:33:54,699 --> 00:33:55,699
Okay.

535
00:33:56,868 --> 00:33:58,078
[speaking French]

536
00:33:58,662 --> 00:34:00,292
All right, turn over the paper.

537
00:34:00,372 --> 00:34:02,502
[interpreter speaking indistinctly]

538
00:34:04,584 --> 00:34:06,254
[Platon] Cory, go easy with the reading.

539
00:34:06,336 --> 00:34:07,626
[camera clicks and winds]

540
00:34:10,507 --> 00:34:12,007
[Platon] <i>What makes this work</i>

541
00:34:12,092 --> 00:34:15,602
<i>is not a calculated argument</i>
<i>that you've scripted.</i>

542
00:34:15,679 --> 00:34:19,429
<i>It's just the beauty and delicacy</i>
<i>of the human condition.</i>

543
00:34:20,725 --> 00:34:23,345
-Pregnant, all from rape?
-[male nurse] Yes, all from rape.

544
00:34:23,436 --> 00:34:25,516
[Platon] All right,
you got to be fast, Cory.

545
00:34:27,774 --> 00:34:28,904
Okay.

546
00:34:29,776 --> 00:34:30,686
Now...

547
00:34:30,777 --> 00:34:36,237
[Platon] <i>I know exactly where, if I reach</i>
<i>my hand, the lens is right there.</i>

548
00:34:36,866 --> 00:34:40,196
<i>I don't want to look down at my camera</i>
<i>to adjust the f-stops.</i>

549
00:34:40,287 --> 00:34:43,787
<i>Because that means I'm taking my eye</i>
<i>off the story for a second.</i>

550
00:34:44,374 --> 00:34:48,214
<i>If I'm losing the glint in your eye</i>
<i>a bit too much,</i>

551
00:34:48,295 --> 00:34:51,755
<i>I'll get you to look just above the lens</i>

552
00:34:51,840 --> 00:34:55,050
<i>and that would just be enough</i>
<i>for your eyes to hit the light.</i>

553
00:34:56,052 --> 00:34:58,392
<i>It's just a twist of the neck now.</i>

554
00:35:01,766 --> 00:35:04,766
<i>Sometimes I just touch my chest</i>
<i>and gesture out,</i>

555
00:35:04,853 --> 00:35:06,523
<i>as if to say "Open up."</i>

556
00:35:06,605 --> 00:35:09,725
[camera clicks and winds]

557
00:35:13,820 --> 00:35:15,490
Black and white, let's move fast.

558
00:35:17,115 --> 00:35:19,775
[gentle music playing]

559
00:35:21,786 --> 00:35:25,866
Can I ask her to tell me
what happened to her?

560
00:35:31,463 --> 00:35:33,973
[Esther in Swahili]
<i>One day I was coming from school</i>

561
00:35:34,049 --> 00:35:35,759
<i>and went to fetch water from a river.</i>

562
00:35:35,842 --> 00:35:40,012
<i>I met a man who told me</i>
<i>that if I didn't have sex with him,</i>

563
00:35:40,096 --> 00:35:42,556
<i>he promised he'd kill me with a knife.</i>

564
00:35:42,641 --> 00:35:45,941
<i>Then after he let me go.</i>

565
00:35:46,019 --> 00:35:49,859
I got treatment, and after,
I gave birth to this baby.

566
00:35:51,733 --> 00:35:53,073
[camera clicks and winds]

567
00:35:57,197 --> 00:35:59,157
[Platon] <i>When I'm really locked in...</i>

568
00:36:01,785 --> 00:36:02,615
Got it.

569
00:36:02,702 --> 00:36:06,162
<i>it's an amazing, terrifying experience,</i>
<i>every time.</i>

570
00:36:07,582 --> 00:36:09,792
There's such strength in everyone here.

571
00:36:10,585 --> 00:36:15,875
In these next few pictures,
channel all that strength from the women.

572
00:36:16,549 --> 00:36:20,349
It goes through your heart,
out, into the camera,

573
00:36:20,428 --> 00:36:22,058
out to the world.

574
00:36:23,848 --> 00:36:25,598
<i>Because if I get it wrong,</i>

575
00:36:25,684 --> 00:36:27,694
<i>I can actually do great harm.</i>

576
00:36:28,853 --> 00:36:29,853
[camera clicks and winds]

577
00:36:29,938 --> 00:36:32,898
<i>It's really important</i>
<i>that my homework is done.</i>

578
00:36:33,733 --> 00:36:35,943
[sighs] All right, it's a bloody wrap.

579
00:36:36,027 --> 00:36:37,897
[general chatter]

580
00:36:51,042 --> 00:36:52,542
[upbeat music playing]

581
00:36:54,254 --> 00:36:58,514
<i>All the things I have learnt about</i>
<i>the difference between right and wrong,</i>

582
00:36:58,591 --> 00:37:01,141
<i>I need to learn these things</i>
<i>through my job.</i>

583
00:37:02,262 --> 00:37:04,722
<i>And if I can pass those values on,</i>

584
00:37:05,724 --> 00:37:06,934
<i>then it's a good thing.</i>

585
00:37:11,813 --> 00:37:15,693
<i>And a lot of the time, to do these things,</i>
<i>I'm away all the time.</i>

586
00:37:36,463 --> 00:37:40,883
<i>Here I am talking about the responsibility</i>
<i>of telling people's stories</i>

587
00:37:40,967 --> 00:37:42,297
<i>and getting it right...</i>

588
00:37:43,720 --> 00:37:46,470
<i>But I also have a responsibility</i>
<i>as a family man.</i>

589
00:37:47,265 --> 00:37:48,175
Shall we get some more?

590
00:37:48,975 --> 00:37:50,935
-All right...
-[girl] What are you going to do?

591
00:37:51,019 --> 00:37:52,689
I don't know. I'm going to take this one

592
00:37:52,771 --> 00:37:54,691
and I am going to use
the same blue as you.

593
00:37:56,399 --> 00:37:58,109
So just the spots, what do you think?

594
00:37:58,193 --> 00:38:01,363
<i>It's funny, because I am actually</i>
<i>the one that freezes time.</i>

595
00:38:03,156 --> 00:38:06,866
<i>So I now know</i>
<i>how precious every moment is.</i>

596
00:38:08,912 --> 00:38:12,542
<i>And I'm trying to squeeze it</i>
<i>so dry every second.</i>

597
00:38:24,385 --> 00:38:25,755
-Cory?
-Yup?

598
00:38:26,846 --> 00:38:30,346
Can you tell me what frame we used
for Esther? Was it frame 12?

599
00:38:31,017 --> 00:38:35,397
No, it was contact one, four C,
frame three.

600
00:38:41,110 --> 00:38:42,070
Got it.

601
00:38:49,994 --> 00:38:51,124
Hmm...

602
00:38:54,749 --> 00:38:56,669
[gentle piano music playing]

603
00:38:58,127 --> 00:38:59,747
Let's have a look at the edits.

604
00:39:00,755 --> 00:39:03,925
[Cory] This is everything thus far
that you've selected.

605
00:39:04,759 --> 00:39:06,259
And then Esther.

606
00:39:06,344 --> 00:39:10,644
So here, there's something beautiful
about just focusing on the baby,

607
00:39:10,723 --> 00:39:13,353
but in this case,

608
00:39:14,602 --> 00:39:16,692
I think you need her.

609
00:39:16,771 --> 00:39:20,151
You can tell she's in pain.
I mean look, there's a scar.

610
00:39:20,233 --> 00:39:23,653
But I've also seen this shape
so many times.

611
00:39:25,238 --> 00:39:29,528
But there's something
totally open about this.

612
00:39:30,785 --> 00:39:35,615
No one's performing.
She's just very open, very raw.

613
00:39:37,292 --> 00:39:39,342
So let's scan it and give it to Bob.

614
00:39:41,713 --> 00:39:46,013
<i>The drum scanner I have was built</i>
<i>by NASA in the '80s.</i>

615
00:39:47,844 --> 00:39:50,644
<i>It does something beautiful to the grain</i>

616
00:39:50,722 --> 00:39:52,852
<i>that you just can't get</i>
<i>with other scanners.</i>

617
00:39:55,518 --> 00:39:58,648
<i>Everything I do is based on the dark room.</i>

618
00:39:59,355 --> 00:40:00,815
[Bob] Let me show you this.

619
00:40:00,899 --> 00:40:04,149
<i>The only way I can bring out</i>
<i>all these elements in a print</i>

620
00:40:04,235 --> 00:40:06,695
<i>is to start isolating different elements</i>

621
00:40:06,779 --> 00:40:08,619
<i>and treat them all</i>
<i>with their own reverence.</i>

622
00:40:08,698 --> 00:40:11,448
I think they're a little intense,
so let's bring them down.

623
00:40:11,951 --> 00:40:13,081
<i>The danger of Photoshop</i>

624
00:40:13,161 --> 00:40:15,791
<i>is that everything is just</i>
<i>a constant sliding scale.</i>

625
00:40:15,872 --> 00:40:18,082
<i>We never use the magic wand,</i>

626
00:40:18,166 --> 00:40:21,996
<i>which is a tool</i>
<i>to just instantly select certain areas.</i>

627
00:40:22,086 --> 00:40:23,756
<i>Everything is hand drawn.</i>

628
00:40:23,838 --> 00:40:24,838
<i>Everything.</i>

629
00:40:24,923 --> 00:40:28,643
And now we're just getting to the bit
where we just have to balance it all out.

630
00:40:28,718 --> 00:40:32,258
<i>With all this amazing technology,</i>
<i>the tools must never dominate us.</i>

631
00:40:32,972 --> 00:40:33,932
I think we're good.

632
00:40:34,599 --> 00:40:35,599
[Bob] Okay.

633
00:40:35,683 --> 00:40:37,643
[expectant, hopeful music playing]

634
00:40:49,280 --> 00:40:50,620
[Platon] It's getting close.

635
00:41:09,801 --> 00:41:10,641
Wow.

636
00:41:10,718 --> 00:41:12,298
[exclaims]

637
00:41:14,889 --> 00:41:15,849
Look at that.

638
00:41:18,017 --> 00:41:19,057
